The paper discusses benchmarking of concurrent priority queues, which is a topic related to data structures and algorithms. Therefore, cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also discusses the implementation of k-LSM priority queue, which is a data structure that is commonly used in databases. This makes cs.DB (Databases) another likely sub-category. The paper also discusses the performance of the priority queues on different types of systems, which is related to operating systems, making cs.OS (Operating Systems) a likely sub-category. The paper also discusses the scalability of the priority queues, which is related to parallel and distributed computing, making cs.PF (Parallel and Distributed Computing) another likely sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the limitations of using throughput benchmark alone to characterize the performance of concurrent priority queues, which is related to distributed computing, making cs.DC (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing) another likely sub-category.
